HEADWORD: Mydaleine
<hw>My*da"le*ine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr.
<grk>myda^n</grk> to be clammy (from decay).]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.
Chem.)</fld> <def>A toxic alkaloid (ptomaine) obtained from putrid flesh
and from herring brines. As a poison it is said to execute profuse
diarrhoea, vomiting, and intestinal inflammation.</def>
<rj><au>Brieger.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mydatoxin</ent>⟦br⟧
